Numerical Methods for PDEs (Spring 2017), Lab 11

Gustav Delius, Richard Southwell

The purpose of this short lab is to reassure everyone that the even if you have a complicated-looking system of parabolic PDEs, the forward-difference method is straightforward to apply. It only has the drawback of requiring a very small timestep. One may therefore like to later go to implicit methods, which are much more clever and tricky and can give an amazing speed-up while at the same time removing stability problems. However I recommend to always initially set up the simple forward-difference method, if only to have something simple to compare the more sophisticated methods against.

For this lab I chose the paper

Tsyganov, M.A., Brindley, J., Holden, A.V., and Biktashev, V.N. (2003). Quasisoliton Interaction of Pursuit-Evasion Waves in a Predator-Prey System. Phys. Rev. Lett. 91, 218102.

It describes the abundance \(Z\) of a predator (you can think of zooplankton if you like) and an abundance \(P\) of prey (phytoplankton) by the set of coupled equations \[ \begin{split} \frac{\partial P}{\partial t} &= D\frac{\partial^2 P}{\partial x^2} +h_- \frac{\partial}{\partial x}P\frac{\partial Z}{\partial x} +\beta P(1-P)-Z\frac{P^2}{P^2+\nu^2},\\ \frac{\partial Z}{\partial t} &= D\frac{\partial^2 Z}{\partial x^2} -h_+ \frac{\partial}{\partial x}Z\frac{\partial P}{\partial x} +\gamma Z\left(\frac{P^2}{P^2+\nu^2}-w\right). \end{split} \]

Here \(D, h_-, h_+, \beta, \nu, \gamma\) are constant parameters.

If this was a proper project report we would now discuss the meaning of these terms a bit, but for now we are only interested in implementing the forward difference method for this somewhat complicated looking set of equations.

Each of the equations contains a linear second-order derivative term that we will discretize as in eq.(2.7) in the lecture notes: \[ \frac{\partial^2 P}{\partial x^2}(x_k,t_j)= \frac{P_{k+1,j}-2P_{k,j}+P_{k-1,j}}{h^2}-O(h^2), \] and similarly for \(\partial^2 Z/\partial x^2\).

Each equation also has a non-linear second-order derivative term that we will discretize as in eq.(2.102) in the lecture notes: \[ \frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(P\frac{\partial Z}{\partial x}\right)(x_k,t_j)= \frac{(P_{k+1,j}-P_{k,j})(Z_{k+1,j}-Z_{k,j}) -(P_{k,j}+P_{k-1,j})(Z_{k,j}-Z_{k-1,j})}{2h^2}+O(h^2), \] and similarly for \(\partial/\partial x(Z\partial P/\partial x)\).

For the time derivatives we use the forward difference formula \[ \frac{\partial P}{\partial t}(x_k,t_j)= \frac{P_{k,j+1}-P_{k,j}}{\tau}+O(\tau) \]

Putting this all together gives us the following explicit method: \[ \begin{split} P_{k,j+1} = P_{k,j} + \tau\Bigg( &\frac{D}{h^2}(P_{k+1,j}-2P_{k,j}+P_{k-1,j})\\ &+\frac{h_-}{2h^2}\Big((P_{k+1,j}-P_{k,j})(Z_{k+1,j}-Z_{k,j}) -(P_{k,j}+P_{k-1,j})(Z_{k,j}-Z_{k-1,j})\Big)\\ &+\beta P_{j,k}(1-P_{j,k})-Z_{j,k}\frac{P_{j,k}^2}{P_{j,k}^2+\nu^2} \Bigg)\\ Z_{k,j+1} = Z_{k,j} + \tau\Bigg( &\frac{D}{h^2}(Z_{k+1,j}-2Z_{k,j}+Z_{k-1,j})\\ &-\frac{h_+}{2h^2}\Big((Z_{k+1,j}-Z_{k,j})(P_{k+1,j}-P_{k,j}) -(Z_{k,j}+Z_{k-1,j})(P_{k,j}-P_{k-1,j})\Big)\\ &+\gamma Z_{j,k}\left(\frac{P_{j,k}^2}{P_{j,k}^2+\nu^2}-w\right) \Bigg) \end{split} \] This scheme has a truncation error of \(O(\tau+h^2)\).

We impose Dirichlet boundary conditions \[ \frac{\partial P}{\partial x}(0,t)=\frac{\partial P}{\partial x}(L,t) =\frac{\partial Z}{\partial x}(0,t)=\frac{\partial Z}{\partial x}(L,t). \]

In order to keep a truncation error of \(O(h^2)\) we use the scheme from section 2.6 in the lecture notes: we introduce points \(x_{-1}\) and \(x_{N+1}\) and use the central-difference formula for the derivative to translate the boundary conditions into expressions for the values of the solution at these points: \[ P_{-1,j}=P_{1,j},~~P_{N+1,j}=P_{N-1,j}, ~~ Z_{-1,j}=Z_{1,j},~~Z_{N+1,j}=Z_{N-1,j}, \] This allows us to use the finite difference equations above with \(k=0\) and \(k=N\).

In R we like to work with entire vectors at a time rather than dealing with each \(x_k\) individually. For that purpose we introduce vectors \[ {\vec P}_j = \begin{pmatrix}P_{0,j}\\P_{1,j}\\\vdots\\P_{N-1,j}\\P_{N,j}\end{pmatrix},~~~ {\vec P}^+_j = \begin{pmatrix}P_{1,j}\\P_{2,j}\\\vdots\\P_{N,j}\\P_{N-1,j}\end{pmatrix},~~~ {\vec P}^-_j = \begin{pmatrix}P_{1,j}\\P_{0,j}\\\vdots\\P_{N-2,j}\\P_{N-1,j}\end{pmatrix} \] and similarly for \(Z\). This will allow us to translate the method into efficient R code below.

We choose a step size \(h\) and introduce the grid points \(x_k = k h\) for \(k=0,\dots,N\)

h <- 0.1
N <- 400
x <- (0:N)*h

and similarly we introduce a step size \(\tau\) and time grid points \(t_j=j\tau\) for \(j=0,\dots M\). However we do not want to save results at each time step, because there are so many of them, and so we split this as \(M = M_1 M_2\) and then only save \(M_1 = 100\) results.

tau <- 0.1
M <- 4000
M1 <- 100
M2 <- round(M/M1)

We create the vector of times at which we save the results

t <- (0:M1)*M2*tau

We initialise two matrices to hold the approximations \(P_{k,j}\) and \(Z_{k,j}\) to the exact solution for \(k=0,\dots,N\) and \(j=0,\dots,M\).

wp <- matrix(0, nrow=N+1, ncol=M1+1)
wz <- matrix(0, nrow=N+1, ncol=M1+1)

We choose parameter values

D <- 0.04
nu <- 0.07
beta <- 1
gamma <- 0.01
w <- 0.004/gamma
hp <- 0
hm <- 0

We determine the steady-state constant solution \((P_0,Z_0)\) to the equations. The equations for this solution are obtained by setting all derivatives equal to zero in the PDEs.

P0 <- uniroot(function(P) P^2/(P^2+nu^2)-w, interval=c(0,1))$root
Z0 <- beta*P0*(1-P0)/w

We will choose an initial condition in which we increase the abundance to the phytoplankton abundance above its equilibrium value near the left end of the interval in order to trigger a plankton bloom there. \[ P(x,0) = P_0 + \begin{cases}0.2(\cos(4\pi x)+1) & \text{ if } x<1/4\\ 0& \text{ otherwise }\end{cases}, ~~~ Z(x,0) = Z_0. \]

Pn <- P0 + ifelse(x<1/4, 0.2*(cos(4*pi*x)+1), 0)
Zn <- Z0 + 0*x  # the +0*x term ensures this is a vector of the same length as x
wp[, 1] <- Pn
wz[, 1] <- Zn

Now we are ready to step through time and at each step update the result according to the formulae derived above. At every \(M_2\)-th step we save the result.

for (j in 1:M1) {
  for (j2 in 1:M2) {
    
    P <- Pn
    Pp <- c(P[2:(N+1)], P[N])
    Pm <- c(P[2], P[1:N])
    
    Z <- Zn
    Zp <- c(Z[2:(N+1)], Z[N-1])
    Zm <- c(Z[2], Z[1:N])
    
    Pn <- P + tau * (
      D/h^2 * (Pp - 2*P + Pm) + 
        hm/(2*h^2) * ((Pp+P)*(Zp-Z)-(P+Pm)*(Z-Zm)) +
        beta*P*(1-P)-Z*P^2/(P^2+nu^2)
    )
    
    Zn <- Z + tau * (
      D/h^2 * (Zp - 2*Z + Zm) - 
        hp/(2*h^2) * ((Zp+Z)*(Pp-P)-(Z+Zm)*(P-Pm)) +
        gamma*Z*(P^2/(P^2+nu^2) - w)
    )
  }
  wp[, j+1] <- Pn
  wz[, j+1] <- Zn
}

Finally we make a plot of the result. Here is the prey abundance:

library(plot3Drgl)
## Loading required package: rgl
## Loading required package: plot3D
persp3D(x, t, wp,
        xlab="x", ylab="t", zlab="P",
        ticktype="detailed", nticks=4)

plotrgl(lighting = TRUE, smooth = TRUE)

Here is the predator abundance:

persp3D(x, t, wz,
        xlab="x", ylab="t", zlab="Z",
        ticktype="detailed", nticks=4)

plotrgl(lighting = TRUE, smooth = TRUE)

We choose an intermediate time and plot both abundances on a 2-d plot:

plot(x, wp[, 51], type="l", ylab="")
lines(x, wz[, 51], lty="dotted")
legend("topleft", legend=c("P", "Z"), lty=c("solid", "dotted"))

This is similar to Figure 1(a) in the paper.

To facilitate exploration of the parameter space, we encapsulate the code we used above in a function.

explicit <- function(deltaP=function(x) 0*x, deltaZ=function(x) 0*x, 
                     D=0.04, nu=0.07, beta=1, gamma=0.01, w=0.4, hp=0, hm=0,
                     L=40, N=400, T=400, M=4000) {
  h <- L/N
  x <- (0:N)*h
  
  tau <- T/M
  M1 <- 100
  M2 <- round(M/M1)
  t <- (0:M1)*M2*tau
  
  wp <- matrix(0, nrow=N+1, ncol=M1+1)
  wz <- matrix(0, nrow=N+1, ncol=M1+1)
  
  P0 <- uniroot(function(P) P^2/(P^2+nu^2)-w, interval=c(0,1))$root
  Z0 <- beta*P0*(1-P0)/w
  Pn <- P0 + deltaP(x)
  Zn <- Z0 + deltaZ(x)
  wp[, 1] <- Pn
  wz[, 1] <- Zn
  
  for (j in 1:M1) {
    for (j2 in 1:M2) {
      
      P <- Pn
      Pp <- c(P[2:(N+1)], P[N])
      Pm <- c(P[2], P[1:N])
      
      Z <- Zn
      Zp <- c(Z[2:(N+1)], Z[N-1])
      Zm <- c(Z[2], Z[1:N])
      
      Pn <- P + tau * (
        D/h^2 * (Pp - 2*P + Pm) + 
          hm/(2*h^2) * ((Pp+P)*(Zp-Z)-(P+Pm)*(Z-Zm)) +
          beta*P*(1-P)-Z*P^2/(P^2+nu^2)
      )
      
      Zn <- Z + tau * (
        D/h^2 * (Zp - 2*Z + Zm) - 
          hp/(2*h^2) * ((Zp+Z)*(Pp-P)-(Z+Zm)*(P-Pm)) +
          gamma*Z*(P^2/(P^2+nu^2) - w)
      )
    }
    wp[, j+1] <- Pn
    wz[, j+1] <- Zn
  }
  list(x=x, t=t, P=wp, Z=wz)
}

We also define the perturbation from the steady-state value for \(P\) that we use in the initial condition.

deltaP <- function(x) ifelse(x<1/4, 0.4*(cos(4*pi*x)+1), 0)

We can now try to reproduce other plots from the paper by changing the value if \(h_+\). Here is Figure 1(b)

sol <- explicit(deltaP=deltaP, hp=0.5, L=130, N=520, T=390, M=3000)
plot(sol$x[280:521], sol$P[280:521, 101], type="l", xlab="x", ylab="")
lines(sol$x[280:521], sol$Z[280:521, 101], lty="dotted")
legend("topleft", legend=c("P", "Z"), lty=c("solid", "dotted"))

And Figure 1(c):

sol <- explicit(deltaP=deltaP, hp=0.9, L=130, N=520, T=330, M=2800)
plot(sol$x[280:521], sol$P[280:521, 101], type="l", xlab="x", ylab="")
lines(sol$x[280:521], sol$Z[280:521, 101], lty="dotted")
legend("topleft", legend=c("P", "Z"), lty=c("solid", "dotted"))

However I think that the authors made a mistake. The above figure, and therefore the figure in the paper, is not a good representation of the actual solution when \(h_+=0.9\). We can see that by getting a more precise solution by decreasing \(\tau\) by increasing the number of time steps to \(M=24000\):

sol <- explicit(deltaP=deltaP, hp=0.9, L=130, N=520, T=330, M=24000)
plot(sol$x[280:521], sol$P[280:521, 101], type="l", xlab="x", ylab="")
lines(sol$x[280:521], sol$Z[280:521, 101], lty="dotted")
legend("topleft", legend=c("P", "Z"), lty=c("solid", "dotted"))

However even with \(M=24000\) steps there are numerical problems with the solution as we can see by making a 3d plot:

persp3D(sol$x, sol$t, sol$Z,
        xlab="x", ylab="t", zlab="Z",
        ticktype="detailed", nticks=4)

There are rapid oscillations in the value of \(Z\) in those places where \(\partial P/\partial x\) is very large. Apparently the fact that \(P\) can change so rapidly means that the cross-diffusion term in the equation for \(Z\) requires a very small time step in our explicit method.

We could hope to improve on this by using an implicit method for the diffusion terms.
